		            		            		            					<!-- start content -->
					<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Directed_Separation_.28d-separation.29">Directed Separation (d-separation)</span></h2>
<p>In the following we denote Probability Distribution with P and a Graph with G.</p>
<p><b>Definition 1</b>: We say that a set of nodes $$\mathbf{X}$$ and a set of nodes $$\mathbf{Y}$$ are d-separated in G given a set of nodes $$\mathbf{Z}$$ if there is no active trail in G between $$\mathbf{X}$$ and $$\mathbf{Y}$$ given $$\mathbf{Z}$$. (Notation: $$d-sep&#95;{G}(\mathbf{X,Y}|\mathbf{Z})$$)</p>
<p><br /></p>
<p><b>Theorem 1</b>: If P factorizes over G, and $$d-sep&#95;{G}(\mathbf{X,Y}|\mathbf{Z})$$ then P satisfies $$\mathbf{X} \perp\mathbf{Y} | \mathbf{Z}$$.</p>
<p><br /></p>
<p><b>Definition 2</b>: If P satisfies $$I(G)$$, we say that G is an I-map (independency map) of P, where $$I(G)$$ denotes the set of independencies that are implicit in the Graph, i.e.: $$I(G) = &#92;{(\mathbf{X}\perp\mathbf{Y}|\mathbf{Z}): d-sep&#95;{G}(\mathbf{X,Y}|\mathbf{Z})&#92;}$$</p>
<p>Note that this definition requires that any independence that is implied by G must hold for the distribution. In other words it doesn't require that the graph G represents all the independencies of the distribution. P may satisfy more independencies.
<br /></p>
<p>See this thread on the forum for the proof of the d-separation theorem: <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="https://class.coursera.org/pgm/forum/thread?thread_id=296">https://class.coursera.org/pgm/forum/thread?thread_id=296</a></p>
